<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1208068/50135673#c21?mode=alone;showrate=1#c21">8+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:158085">commonmass</a>, <a href="/user/uid:160205">indie17</a>, <a href="/user/uid:317476">koosah</a>, <a href="/user/uid:38699">JayBat</a>, <a href="/user/uid:182885">stone clearing</a>, <a href="/user/uid:67799">417els</a>, <a href="/user/uid:69865">koNko</a>, <a href="/user/uid:171526">Nada Lemming</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>First, the concept of a single composite number for intelligence is troubling, since it's not entirely clear that intelligence is definable as a single entity. &nbsp;This reification of intelligence is cultural... what, precisely and specifically, is meant by intelligence? &nbsp;And how do you measure it with a single number? &nbsp;This is my biggest complaint.. I'm not convinced it measures something useful. &nbsp;There may be ways of measuring abstract reasoning (partially culturally determined), linguistic skills (culturally determined) and mathematical ability (quite possibly the only form of intelligence that may be more genetic than not). &nbsp;But you can't lump everything together and call it "intelligence".</p>
<p>Second, IQ testing is always rooted in culture, even if the psychologists designing IQ tests think it is not. &nbsp;</p>
<p>There's such a long and grim history of racism and fraud and sloppy methodology in IQ testing that the whole thing should give anyone pause. &nbsp;Read "The Mis-Measure of Man" by Steven Jay Gould, published in the early 80's, for a detailed critique and expose of that whole sordid history. It was a formative book for me as a college student, learning and leaving behind my politically conservative upbringing. &nbsp;I feel as if I know this shitheel who wrote this report already, having read about similar efforts to use IQ to define racial difference in the 1880s, 1920's and 1940's.</p>

  </div>
